#use request to download tsv file from a website
url ='https://d17h27t6h515a5.cloudfront.net/topher/2017/August/599fd2ad_image-predictions/image-predictions.tsv'
response = requests.get(url)

with open (url.split('/')[-1], mode = 'wb') as file:
    file.write(response.content)
    
#read downloaded file (tsv)

df2 = pd.read_csv('image-predictions.tsv', sep = ('\t'))

API Data¶

In [4]:
consumer_key = 'HIDDEN'
consumer_secret = 'HIDDEN'
access_token = 'HIDDEN'
access_secret = 'HIDDEN'

auth = OAuthHandler(consumer_key, consumer_secret)
auth.set_access_token(access_token, access_secret)

api = tweepy.API(auth, wait_on_rate_limit=True)


tweet_ids = df1.tweet_id.values
len(tweet_ids)

# Query Twitter's API for JSON data for each tweet ID in the Twitter archive
count = 0
fails_dict = {}
start = timer()
# Save each tweet's returned JSON as a new line in a .txt file
with open('tweet_json.txt', 'w') as outfile:
    # This loop will likely take 20-30 minutes to run because of Twitter's rate limit
    for tweet_id in tweet_ids:
        count += 1
        print(str(count) + ": " + str(tweet_id))
        try:
            tweet = api.get_status(tweet_id, tweet_mode='extended')
            print("Success")
            json.dump(tweet._json, outfile)
            outfile.write('\n')
        except tweepy.TweepError as e:
            print("Fail")
            fails_dict[tweet_id] = e
            pass
end = timer()
print(end - start)
print(fails_dict)

df3= pd.read_json('tweet-json.txt', lines = True)

Quality¶

df1¶

  • tweet-id should be in str
  • Timestamp in str format, should be in datetime.
  • Erroneous datatypes (in_reply_to_status_id, in_reply_to_user_id, retweeted_status_id, retweeted_status_user_id ), should be in int instead of float, or maybe in str because we dont need to calculate anything with these collumns.
  • rating_nominator and rating_denominator may have incorrect values.
  • Name collumn has invalid values such as None, a.

df2¶

  • tweet-id should be in str

df3¶

  • All id collumns should be in str

Tidiness¶

df1¶

  • 4 types of dogs (doggo,floofer,pupper,puppo) can be in the same collumn.
  • Some non-nessessary collumns can be deleted.

df2¶

  • Some non-nessessary collumns can be deleted.
  • Merge into one dataset.

df3¶

  • Some non-nessessary collumns can be deleted.
  • Merge into one dataset.

Cleaning¶

Tidiness¶

In [24]:
#make copies of each dataframe to clean
df1_clean= df1.copy()
df2_clean= df2.copy()
df3_clean= df3.copy()
In [25]:
#first we need to merge 3 data into one dataframe
#change collumn id in df3_clean into tweet_id
df3_clean.rename(columns = {'id':'tweet_id'}, inplace = True)
In [26]:
#drop all unnessessary columns in df3_clean, only get 3 columns in df3_clean
df3_clean= df3_clean[['tweet_id', 'retweet_count','favorite_count']]

Define¶

Combine 4 dog types into one column

Code¶

In [32]:
dog = ['doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper', 'puppo']
list1= list(df_master.columns)
list2 = []
for x in list1:
    if x in dog:
        continue
    list2.append(x)
print(list2)
print(dog)

['tweet_id', 'in_reply_to_status_id', 'in_reply_to_user_id', 'timestamp', 'source', 'text', 'expanded_urls', 'rating_numerator', 'rating_denominator', 'name', 'jpg_url', 'img_num', 'p1', 'p1_conf', 'p1_dog', 'p2', 'p2_conf', 'p2_dog', 'p3', 'p3_conf', 'p3_dog', 'retweet_count', 'favorite_count']

Define¶

Remove html from text

Code¶

In [63]:
def remove_last_line_from_text(s):
    return s[:s.find('http')]

df_master.text= df_master.text.apply(remove_last_line_from_text)

Define¶

Make year, month, day_of_week column

Code¶

In [65]:
df_master['year'] = df_master['timestamp'].dt.year
df_master['month'] = df_master['timestamp'].dt.month
df_master['day_of_week']= df_master['timestamp'].dt.weekday
In [66]:
df_master['month'].replace(1, 'January', inplace=True)
df_master['month'].replace(2, 'February', inplace=True)
df_master['month'].replace(3, 'March', inplace=True)
df_master['month'].replace(4, 'April', inplace=True)
df_master['month'].replace(5, 'May', inplace=True)
df_master['month'].replace(6, 'June', inplace=True)
df_master['month'].replace(7, 'July', inplace=True)
df_master['month'].replace(8, 'August', inplace=True)
df_master['month'].replace(9, 'September', inplace=True)
df_master['month'].replace(10, 'October', inplace=True)
df_master['month'].replace(11, 'November', inplace=True)
df_master['month'].replace(12, 'December', inplace=True)
In [67]:
df_master['day_of_week'].replace(0, 'Monday', inplace=True)
df_master['day_of_week'].replace(1, 'Tuesday', inplace=True)
df_master['day_of_week'].replace(2, 'Wednesday', inplace=True)
df_master['day_of_week'].replace(3, 'Thursday', inplace=True)
df_master['day_of_week'].replace(4, 'Friday', inplace=True)
df_master['day_of_week'].replace(5, 'Saturday', inplace=True)
df_master['day_of_week'].replace(6, 'Sunday', inplace=True)

Define¶

Create dog name from text column and create new dog name column

Code¶

In [69]:
def get_dog_name(x):
    return x[:x.find('.')]

text = df_master.text
dog_name = text.apply(get_dog_name)
In [70]:
df_master['dog_name']= dog_name.str.rsplit(' ', 1).str[-1].str.strip('""()\' ')
In [71]:
#drop old name column
df_master= df_master.drop('name', axis=1)
In [72]:
dog_name =[]
for name in list(df_master['dog_name']):
    if name.istitle():
        dog_name.append(name)
    else:
        dog_name.append('None')
df_master['dog_name']= dog_name

Create count_url column

Code¶

count_url= df_master.expanded_urls.str.split(',').str.len()
In [76]:
df_master['count_url']= count_url

Define¶

Create column for dog sex: male or female

Code¶

In [78]:
dog_sex =[]
for text in list(df_master.text):
    if 'He' in text or 'he'in text or 'his'in text or 'him' in text:
        dog_sex.append('Male')
    else:
        dog_sex.append('Female')
df_master['dog_sex']= dog_sex

Check¶

In [79]:
df_master.dog_sex.value_counts()
Out[79]:
Male      1880
Female      91
Name: dog_sex, dtype: int64

def bar_chart(locations, heights,labels):
    plt.figure(figsize = (20,8))
    plt.bar(locations, heights, tick_label=labels)
    return plt
In [90]:

plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=20)
Out[90]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Count')
